Module 3: Excel & Data Analytics (7.5 Hours)

From Raw Data to Business Insights

Author

Dr Aniruddha Bonnerjee

Abstract
Session 1: Befriending the data and preparing for analytics

Session 1: Befriending the Data + Cleaning Fundamentals

Duration: 1.5 hours

Session Objective

By the end of this session, you will be able to: - Understand how real business datasets are structured - Identify what makes a dataset âcleanâ or âmessyâ - Remove duplicate records using Excel tools - Handle missing values with proper documentation - Use IF functions to create status flags - Translate business questions into data questions

Key Concepts

Data vs Information vs Insight

Data â Raw facts and numbers
Example: Sales = â¹45,000

Information â Organized and contextualized data
Example: Maharashtra sales in March = â¹45,000

Insight â Meaningful pattern or conclusion that drives decisions
Example: Maharashtra sales dropped 15% vs February, requiring immediate investigation

Understanding Dataset Structure

Every dataset has: - Rows = Individual records/transactions - Columns = Variables/attributes - Headers = Column names (should be clear and consistent) - Data Types = Numbers, text, dates, categories

Ask yourself: - What does each row represent? - What does each column measure? - What time period does this cover? - Are there any obvious patterns just from looking?

Todayâs Dataset

Company Sales Performance Data

This dataset contains sales transactions from a regional company across multiple states, branches, and product lines. Itâs similar to what a regional manager or business analyst might work with daily.

Variables include: - State - Month - Branch Location - Product Line - Sales (in â¹) - Sales Target (in â¹) - Sales Channel - Customer Segment - Transaction ID

Your task: Open it, explore it, clean it, and make it analysis-ready.

Common Data Quality Issues

As you explore the dataset, watch for:

Issue What to Look For Why It Matters
Missing Values Blank cells Canât analyze what you donât have
Duplicates Same transaction appearing twice Inflates totals, skews analysis
Inconsistent Labels âMumbaiâ vs âmumbaiâ Makes grouping/comparison difficult
Outliers Values that seem wrong Could be errors or important signals
Incomplete Records Rows with multiple blanks May need to be removed or flagged

Part 2: Identify Issues (15 minutes)

Guided Exploration

Now actively search for problems. This is detective work! First, click anywhere in the excel sheet, then select Data from the top menu and clicking on Filter in the ribbon that appears (look for the funnel icon). Now little arrows (â¼) will appear on all the column headers allowing us to explore the data more effectively.

Tip

The Data Menu is very powerful. Take a moment to examine the ribbon that appears. You can do many things here - we will see some of the useful functions.

  2. Press Ctrl + Down Arrow to jump through data

  4. Repeat for Sales (column E), Sales_Target (column F)

  2. Look at Product Line names - consistent capitalization?

Part 3: Remove Duplicates (15 minutes)

Why Duplicates Are Dangerous

Imagine calculating total sales. If a â¹50,000 transaction appears twice, your total is inflated by â¹50,000. Multiply this across hundreds of records, and your CEO makes decisions based on false revenue numbers.

Bottom line: Duplicates destroy trust in your data.

How to Remove Duplicates in Excel

First make a copy of the data in another excel sheet. You can do this by highlighting all the data by pressing Ctrl-A (select all), then pressing Ctrl-C (for Copy), clicking on the + icon at the bottom of the excel sheet ribbon to get a new blank excel sheet (Sheet1), and then pressing Ctrl-V (for Paste) in the top left hand corner cell (A1).

Rename the new sheet Clean Data. You can do this by right-clicking on Sheet1 and then typing Clean Data as the new name for that sheet.

Method 1: Using Excelâs Built-in Tool (Recommended)

  1. Select your entire dataset
    • Press Ctrl-A
  2. Access Remove Duplicates
    • Go to Data tab in ribbon
    • Click Remove Duplicates button
  3. Configure the tool
    • Excel will show a dialog box
    • Make sure âMy data has headersâ is checked
    • Make sure All columns are checked/selected
  4. Execute and document
    • Click OK
    • Excel will show: âX duplicate values found and removed; Y unique values remainâ
    • Write this number down! You need it for your cleaning log

Example output:

25 duplicate values found and removed; 1040 unique values remain.

Part 4: Handle Missing Values (20 minutes)

The Missing Data Decision Framework

Not all missing data should be handled the same way. You need to make decisions based on context.

Three Questions to Ask:

  1. How much is missing?
    • If 50% of sales data is missing, the dataset might be unusable
    • If 5% is missing, you can work with it
  2. Is it random or systematic?
    • Random: Missing values scattered throughout
    • Systematic: One branch never reports sales (bigger problem!)
  3. Whatâs the impact of deleting vs keeping?
    • Will you lose critical information?
    • Can you work around it?

Strategy: First Flag, then Delete Rows with Missing Sales

When to use: Sales is your primary analysis variable. A transaction without sales data is useless. It points to data problems. However, before deleting the data, it would be useful to flag the rows with missing sales data so we can first analyze the problems with missing data (maybe in some states/months?).

For this we will use the âIFâ function in Excel.

Introduction to IF Function

Tip

The IF function is one of Excelâs most powerful tools. It allows you to make decisions with data.

Basic Syntax:

=IF(condition, value_if_true, value_if_false)

Real-world analogy:

IF it's raining, bring an umbrella, otherwise bring sunglasses

A. Steps to flag missing/blank sales data:

  1. Create a new column

    • Go to cell J1
    • Type Sales_Flag to create a flag for missing sales values and name the column

  2. Write the IF formula

    • Click cell J2 (first data row)
    • Type this formula:
    =IF(ISBLANK(F2), 0, 1)
    • Press Enter

  3. Understand the formula

    • ISBLANK(F2) checks if cell F2 is empty (ISBLANK)
    • If TRUE â displays 0 for blank data
    • If FALSE â displays 1 for valid data

  4. Copy formula down

    • Click on cell J2. You will notice a small square in the bottom-right corner
    • Double-click the small square (fill handle) - it will automatically copy the formula to the remaining rows
    • Or copy and paste down manually

  5. Select all the rows in column J (from J2:J1001)

    • At the bottom of the screen, you will see count, sum and average.

  6. Note them down. What do they mean?

B. Steps to delete missing/blank sales data:

  1. Apply a filter as we did earlier by selecting Dataâ>Filter (funnel icon)

    • Small dropdown arrows (â¼) appear in headers

  2. Filter Sales_Flag column

    • Click dropdown arrow in Sales_Flag (column J)
    • Uncheck âSelect Allâ
    • Select 0 (we are looking at data with blank sales)
    • Click OK

  3. Examine the data with blank Sales

    • Do you notice any patterns in the month column?

    • Which months/years had most blank Sales data?

    • Keep a note of your observations

  4. Select and delete filtered rows

    • Click on row number of first visible row
    • Shift + Click on last visible row
    • Right-click â Delete Row
    • Select Yes in the dialogue box. that appears

  5. Clear the filter

    • Click on the small arrow again in Sales_Flag
    • Click on clear filter. The rest of your data will be visible.
    • There will no longer be any sales data missing

  6. Document your decision

    Removed 20 rows with missing Sales values
because Sales is a primary metric for our analysis.

Do the same steps for Missing Sales_Target

When to use: Sales_Target is informational, not critical. Some branches might not have targets set yet.

Steps: Repeat A and B from above but this time for the Sales_Target column

  1. Create a new column

    • Click on cell K1
    • Type Target_Flag to give the column a header name

  2. Write the IF formula

    • Click cell K2 (first data row)
    • Type this formula:
    =IF(ISBLANK(G2), 0, 1)
    • Press Enter

  3. Understand the formula

    • ISBLANK(G2) checks if cell G2 is empty
    • If TRUE â displays 0
    • If FALSE â displays 1

  4. Copy formula down

    • Click on cell K2
    • Double-click the small square in bottom-right corner (fill handle). The remaining rows will automatically get filled with the formula.
    • Or copy and paste down manually
    • Note what appears in the bottom of the screen (RHS).
    • Note down the count, average and sum.

  5. Document your decision

    Created Target_Status flag for missing Sales_Target values.
Preserved all records for analysis. Can now delete by 0 (No Target)
vs 1 (Target)" to understand target-setting patterns. 
Note down the values observed from Step 4 above.

  6. Remove rows with no Target_Sales by following the same steps as before.

    Note down how many rows were removed.

Your Documentation Should Include

For your cleaning log, write:

1. Flagged rows with missing Sales_Target
   - Created Target_Flag column using IF function
   - Reason: Target data is supplementary; transaction data still valuable
   - Pattern observed: Missing Targets & Sales in West Bengal, UP mostly

Part 5: Further Examples with IF (25 minutes)

Example 1: Target Achievement Flag

Letâs create a column that shows whether each transaction met its sales target.

Step 1: Insert new column - Insert a column next to Target_Flag - Name it: Performance by typing it in cell L1.

Step 2: Write the formula - Click on first data cell in Performance column - Type:

=IF(F2>=G2,1,0)

Step 3: Understand the logic - F2>=G2 asks: âIs Sales greater than or equal to Target?â - If YES â 1 (Target Met) - If NO â 0 (Target Missed)

Step 4: Copy down - Double-click fill handle or copy down manually.

Step 5: Note what is written in the bottom right corner of the screen.

â You now have a clear performance flag for every transaction!

Example 2: Performance Rating (Nested IF)

Letâs get more sophisticated with a three-tier rating.

Create a new column: Performance_Rating Flag in Column M. Go to cell M1 and type Performance_Rating to give this column a name. Then move to cell M2 and type the formula below.

Formula:

=IF(F2>=G2*1.1, "Excellent", IF(F2>=G2, "Good", "Needs Improvement"))

Logic breakdown: 1. First check: Did sales exceed target by 10% or more? â âExcellentâ 2. If not, second check: Did sales at least meet target? â âGoodâ 3. If not â âNeeds Improvementâ

This is called a ânested IFâ - one IF inside another.

Example 3: High-Value Transaction Flag

Create a flag for Sales transactions above â¹75,000.

Column name: High_Value

Formula:

=IF(F2>75000, "High Value", "Standard")

Simple but powerful for filtering and analysis later!

Part 6: Think About Questions (Ongoing)

Throughout the session, keep asking yourself:

Questions This Dataset CAN Answer

Think about whatâs actually in the data. Examples:

  1. Which state has the highest total sales?
    • We have State and Sales columns â Yes!
  2. Are sales targets being met across different channels?
    • We have Sales, Sales_Target, and Sales_Channel â Yes!
  3. Which product line generates the most sales?
    • We have Product_Line and Sales â Yes!
  4. How do B2B sales compare to B2C sales?
    • We have Customer_Segment and Sales â Yes!
  5. Whatâs the average transaction value by state?
    • We have State and Sales â Yes!

Questions This Dataset CANNOT Answer

Think about whatâs missing. Examples:

  1. Why did sales drop in March?
    • We have numbers but no context (no reason field) â No!
  2. What do customers think about our products?
    • No customer feedback or satisfaction data â No!
  3. How do our prices compare to competitors?
    • No competitor pricing data â No!
  4. Which marketing campaigns drove the most sales?
    • No campaign or marketing data â No!
  5. What is the profit margin on each transaction?
    • We have sales but no profit data â No! (Unless we add it via lookup in another table where such information exists. We will do this in Session 2)

Why This Matters

Understanding what you CANâT answer is as important as knowing what you CAN answer. It: - Prevents you from making claims beyond your data - Helps you identify what additional data you need - Makes you a more credible analyst

For your deliverable, write: - 3 specific questions this dataset CAN answer - 2 specific questions it CANNOT answer - Brief explanation of why for each

Common Mistakes to Avoid

â Deleting data without documenting why - Always keep a cleaning log

â Not keeping a backup of original data - Save a copy before cleaning

â Not checking your formulas - Always verify on a few rows manually

â Assuming missing data is random - Always investigate patterns in missing data

Key Takeaways

â Always befriend your data first - Donât jump into analysis before understanding what you have

â Question everything - Just because data exists doesnât mean itâs correct or complete

â Data has limits - Knowing what you CANâT answer is as important as knowing what you CAN

â Context matters - Numbers without context are just numbers

â Document your decisions - Future you (and your boss) will thank you

â Clean data is the foundation - No analysis is reliable without it

â Always backup data before cleaning - You will lose the original data otherwise
